@joel-costigliola  Sorry... I saw your message this weekend but my company's VPN was down and I could not get you the info.

I am using Notepad++ instead of Eclipse.

I am using AssertJ 3.3.0 and below is the output from "java -version".

```
java version "1.8.0_72"
Java(TM) SE Runtime Environment (build 1.8.0_72-b15)
Java HotSpot(TM) 64-Bit Server VM (build 25.72-b15, mixed mode)
```

I looked at your code and noticed you were using specific types on your Maps. So I did some more testing and found out that if you don't specify your types, then AssertJ will not compile, but Java is OK with it.

This first block of code compile just fine.

```
Map<String, String> map2 = new java.util.HashMap<>();
map2.put("Key1","Value1");
map2.put("Key2","Value2");
Assertions.assertThat(map2).as("").containsOnlyKeys("Key1","Key2");
```

This second block does not compile.  Notice I am not specifying the Map type for map1.

```
Map map1 = new java.util.HashMap<>();
map1.put("Key1","Value1");
map1.put("Key2","Value2");
Assertions.assertThat(map1).as("").containsOnlyKeys("Key1","Key2");
```

This also does not work...

```
Map<?,?> map1 = new java.util.HashMap<>();
map1.put("Key1","Value1");
map1.put("Key2","Value2");
Assertions.assertThat(map1).as("").containsOnlyKeys("Key1","Key2");
```

More feedback on the example with widlcard

``` java
Map<?, ?> map1 = new java.util.HashMap<>();
map1.put("Key1", "Value1"); // COMPILE ERROR
map1.put("Key2", "Value2"); // COMPILE ERROR
assertThat(map1).containsOnlyKeys("Key1", "Key2"); // COMPILE ERROR
assertThat(map1).as("").containsOnlyKeys("Key1", "Key2"); // COMPILE ERROR
```

All the compilation errors comes from the fact that we don't know what is in `map1` thus we can't put or check anything from it.

I have fixed the behavior for raw Map and the following test now passes:

``` java
@Test
public void raw_map_assertion_and_descirption_using_as() {
  Map map1 = new java.util.HashMap<>();
  map1.put("Key1", "Value1");
  map1.put("Key2", "Value2");
  assertThat(map1).as("").containsOnlyKeys("Key1", "Key2");
}
```

Awesome!  Thanks!

